{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:31:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.03,0.05,0.75,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6181"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6181"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90489"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"3874"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"6308"},{"type":"tags","id":"9378"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11644"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42890"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43424"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of back pain and recurrent fractures over the past year. She underwent menopause at age 52. She has a medical history of mild hypertension and does not take any regular medications except ramipril. She has never smoked and does not consume alcohol excessively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination reveals loss of height and kyphosis. Plain radiograph of the spine shows a healed compression fracture of the L1 vertebra with 30% loss of height, with no history of trauma. Dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry scan reveals a T-score of -3.2 at the lumbar spine and -2.8 at the hip.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium and vitamin D supplementation alone","Menopausal hormonal therapy","Imaging studies to assess for metastatic bone disease","Initiate treatment with bisphosphonates","Initiate treatment with denosumab"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-menopausal osteoporosis, characterised by reduced bone density and increased fracture susceptibility following menopause. The combination of fragility fracture, physical findings of height loss and kyphosis, and DEXA scan T-scores of -3.2 (lumbar spine) and -2.8 (hip) confirms severe osteoporosis requiring pharmacological intervention. A loss of vertebral height \u226520% is consistent with osteoporotic fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisphosphonates\u003C/strong\u003E are the first-line pharmacological therapy for post-menopausal osteoporosis. They inhibit osteoclast-mediated bone resorption, improve bone mineral density, and significantly reduce fracture risk. Common options include oral alendronate or risedronate, or intravenous zoledronic acid. They have an established safety profile and proven long-term efficacy in preventing vertebral and non-vertebral fractures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a RANK ligand inhibitor that effectively reduces fracture risk. It is given subcutaneously 6-monthly. In a 65-year-old patient, bisphosphonates are preferred because denosumab carries risks of rebound bone loss and increased fracture risk upon discontinuation, particularly affecting the spine. Long-term use beyond ten years raises concerns about atypical femoral fractures, and patients require transition to bisphosphonate therapy when discontinuing denosumab to prevent rebound effects. For these reasons, denosumab is usually only prescribed for people with a life expectancy of ten years or less. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMenopausal hormonal therapy\u003C/strong\u003E can improve bone density but is primarily indicated for vasomotor menopausal symptoms. Its role in osteoporosis is limited to primary prevention in recently menopausal women, not secondary prevention in patients with established fractures like this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium and vitamin D supplementation alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for treating established osteoporosis with fractures. While these supplements are important adjuncts to ensure adequate bone mineralisation (recommended when dietary calcium is less than 1300 mg daily and to achieve 25-hydroxyvitamin D levels ideally above 70 nmol/L), they cannot adequately reduce fracture risk in severe osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImaging studies to assess for metastatic bone disease\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this straightforward case of post-menopausal osteoporosis. The patient lacks red flags such as unexplained weight loss, cancer history, or atypical bone pain patterns that would suggest secondary causes of bone loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-menopausal osteoporosis, resulting from oestrogen depletion, predisposes women to bone fractures, particularly in the spine, hips, and wrists.","Bisphosphonates are first-line treatment for post-menopausal osteoporosis due to their proven efficacy and safety profile.","Denosumab is typically reserved as second-line therapy due to rebound fracture risk upon discontinuation and concerns with long-term use."],"references":["Bhatnagar A, Kekatpure AL. Postmenopausal Osteoporosis: A Literature Review. Cureus. 2022 Sep 20;14(9):e29367. doi: 10.7759/cureus.29367. PMID: 36299953; PMCID: PMC9586717.","Keen MU, Reddivari AKR. Osteoporosis in Females. [Updated 2023 Jun 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559156/","RACGP. Osteoporosis management and fracture prevention in post-menopausal women and men \u003E 50 years of age \u2013 Summary of recommendations [Internet]. RACGP. 2024 [cited 2025 Apr 14]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/osteoporosis/summary-of-recommendations","Shoback D, Rosen CJ, Black DM, Cheung AM, Murad MH, Eastell R. Pharmacological Management of Osteoporosis in Postmenopausal Women: An Endocrine Society Guideline Update. The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology \u0026 Metabolism [Internet]. 2020 Mar 1;105(3):587\u201394. Available from: https://academic.oup.com/jcem/article/105/3/587/5739968"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90489"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90489","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90489"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T12:16:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T12:18:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6181"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"qu